The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Perhaps
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer practically all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Perhaps this one will not wait long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming charges, there is probably a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile providers, SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a battle announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile providers like to denounce the fact that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
The Chair of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ) often agrees with Pavel Dvořák, who had often said in the past that there was no place for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of chances (by the way, it would probably find hardly any frequencies).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which then also the classical mobile providers had to react.
Even before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices in the UK as in the Czech Republic.
But it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don ’ t need to look for examples for long.
In February we reported about the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in winning more than 100 thousand customers, making it the fifth largest supplier in the country.
The Penta financial group, which owns U: fon in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can concentrate on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
You do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually distinguish themselves as low-cost providers - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobile king in Poland shows, it can also be a good move to put on a non-clichéd target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and trust," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
Difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could take root in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the services offered. "
In the Czech Republic, the mobile providers say
But it is almost certain that when a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
It will rather lead to a market entry of mobilking in other countries of our region, "says Jana Studničková, press officer of the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
It indirectly confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Their interest in launching a virtual mobile phone provider has long been demonstrated by the GTS Novera Group, which wants to take a further step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering not only fixed and mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already achieved progress in negotiations with some of them, "said Pavel Kaidl, spokesperson for the group.
Perhaps better times are coming now.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not assume that there is room for a fully-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has addressed us ", says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other providers point to the specifics of the Czech market.
The press spokesperson of T Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the O2 declaration: "So far we have not found a viable and mutually advantageous project on which one could build further."
And she adds: "By the end of the year, hardly any virtual provider will appear in the net of TMobile.
At this moment we would have to have a concrete offer already, in order to be able to think so in the short term. "
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open for negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we regard as the best from the customer ’ s point of view.
Vodafone ’ s main strategy in this area is to search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet. ”
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decline in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the emergence of U: fon.
Probably the strongest pressure in the direction of ČTÚ at the moment, when U: fon came onto the market, came from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTU websites.
But just U: fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive field of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on his services. "
Given this approach by mobile operators, however, the absolute disinterest of Czech regulators is surprising.
It is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately, unlike Britain and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in Czech.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem to his quite typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile operator would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential prospective customers was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classical providers ", said Kristián Chalupa of the department of external relations of the ÚOHS in his answer to our request.
Representatives of providers would not surprise such a formulation.
This is more than questionable from an authority that represents consumer interests, among other things, to ensure that no one is abusing its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
But probably the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction do not belong to the interests of ÚOHS.
Really shocking in this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile providers, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it really is just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely identical fuel price at the filling stations is surely only coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs of action against competition in this matter, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably missing from the telecoms regulator, "said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, elaborated by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
None of the Czech mobile providers has a dominant position on such a market.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the cellular operator has - logically - a monopoly for its net.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if one does not go along with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile providers are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) prove that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to ČTÚ is then a quite common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS dissociates itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act, it has not been possible to enforce the extension of the competences of ČTÚ to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS need to know all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's already possible when nobody looks
Nevertheless, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider remains, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partly public.
Usually, these are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile telephone services offer for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach selected ones.
The joke of the thing is that the company acts as a classical company customer vis-à-vis the operator, who orders a large amount of SIM tickets.
As an important customer he receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it can be a violation of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal, which can lead to an end to the cooperation with the corresponding company," answered Martina Kemrová on our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not get around with those responsible for mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, they may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
In fact, they do not derive any negligible profits from the activities of these companies, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such kinds of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
Furthermore, they must accept that the SIM debit card does not run on their name in their phone, so they cannot have it fully as normal customers of mobile providers. "
But this alone should at least happen strangely to the ČTÚ.
There is also another question for ÚOHS.
Do mobile providers close their eyes to such a procedure, why are they blocking a virtual provider?
It should be added that ÚOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to contend with the declaration of providers that they do not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been pointed out several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers resulted in a significant price decline in the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classical providers have tried to prevent their emergence more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies intervened precisely at these moments, which did not attempt to safeguard the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Be it through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator emerged, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are throwing themselves into the whole case like a hot potato.
On the basis of our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that uncertainty in the competences in these cases is more than favourable.
But let us not throw the gun into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon emerges, the Czech mobile market may soon be set in motion again.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile provider, ÚOHS will not remain idle when it comes to refusing (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will not call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Find the best out
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech State Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented in a ceremony the new recordings of the national anthem Wo ist mein Heimatland.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo singing, in choral version and in an instrumental version.
The vocal version was taken by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful anthems.
He had already told the Czech Radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices for the solo versions, which are distinctive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried to keep a clear diction with both and then with the choir, so that the text can be understood well, so that a harmony can be achieved", says the conductor.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was performed for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Ständetheater in the originally Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music came from František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously accepted it.
The first verse of the song became an organic part of the national anthem after the birth of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
One of the seven state symbols remained it even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
