On Wednesday, Prague ’ s transport services will also be transported on a chip for the first time
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will go down in the history of Prague ’ s transport companies as a date on which the first passengers who carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket will enter an underground train, tram or bus.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the chip card Opencard.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or yearly coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time put it on their chip card, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the subway stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons have also been available on the website of transport companies www.dpp.cz since yesterday.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the Internet sale can really forget the output window in the U Bahn stations, where they had to wait regularly for their paper tickets in long queues.
You buy the coupon over the Internet, it is played onto the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"In these places, a desk with trained staff is also available to travellers who advise interested parties on the purchase of the Internet and also put the coupon on the map", says the speaker of the project Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on the Opencard on self-service machines, which are installed in some U-Bahn Vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket valuers, passengers may have noticed them already in the underground stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year it should be eighty," Opatrný adds.
Controls the coupon instead of the driver's machine
Operating the machines that will work from tomorrow is easy.
You only have to insert the chip card, and the previously acquired coupon plays itself.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, with which mainly the inhabitants of the municipalities of the region Central Bohemia get to the capital.
"On trains belonging to the Prague integrated traffic, the train attendants have read devices with which they can check the validity period of the coupons by time and zone", explains Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid the ticket control. This organization compiles the timetables for the Prague transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the ticket office with the driver.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be presented to the driver, but the Opencard must be placed in a marked place at the side of the checkout.
The driver controls the validity of the coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons, nothing is easier than to ask the driver for this information," said Drápal.
A passenger who does not use suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon will end can go to the self-service machines, where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information about the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the US
The Sudeten Germans had asked in 1945 for the integration of the Bohemian Forest into the United States.
This emerges from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With such a desire some groups of Sudeten Germans should have turned to the US president in 1945.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter which has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
