Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach flees in danger, that means that she also feels fear?
The neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
Only how could one check if they feel the same when they behave like us?
The Internet publication "Edge" has published contributions by famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far where we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and address questions of sensation or generally of consciousness, we enter rough terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as many other animals: it turns dead, flees or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists discover a comparable subjective experience.
I do not believe that, however.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits associated almost always with the human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the execution / control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in the other primates and seems to be completely lacking in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is therefore reason to believe that man even differs from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity might lie in the linguistic nature of man: since such a large part of his experience is connected with language, it often means that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, one could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, however it may be, probably very different from most of our consciousness states.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine how consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks refer to the content of the conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
One could study the processes of consciousness of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But with this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one shifts rather to the neural correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: Both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasises the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the creation of visualization.
What results in the sensations?
I refer them to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the immune system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
From this point of view, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the Cortex, which distinguish primates and, in particular, people.
Combined with the linguistic nature, fine gradations of sensation arise, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states, in order to attribute them to ourselves as well as others.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, says that sensations from more primitive activities in the body emotional regions of the cortex and brain stem are similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in intergenerational sensations.
In theory, I cannot contradict this, but consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears like fear in rats and people is likely to feel the same in both cases: but how can one check whether rats and people feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees in danger if she also feels fear?
In my eyes, mere behavioural similarity cannot yet prove equality of experience.
While the neural comparison continues to help: rats and humans have similar brain strains, scavenger do not even have a brain.
But is the brain strain responsible for sensations?
And even if one could prove this for the human being: How did one prove it with rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I didn't know how to prove that.
And because their sensations probably differ fundamentally from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is waving at the neural level, provided that the same is measured for rats and people.
As I do not research language and consciousness in rats, so do not sensations, I do not know whether they exist.
You may think this is short-sighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than running constantly against a wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
