The pride and the strains in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the excesses of the amusement parks in the vicinity of Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of Afro ’ s American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first completely black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city she describes - and which made her a tourist destination by taking her up in the Florida travel guide, which was produced by the federal writer project at the time of the depression - is and remains in many respects a place of very special variety.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified and private as in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he does not know what escapes him."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open conversation about racial relations, many here are still sorry to be observed by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told," says Hortense Jones, 59, a native of the city and a parish member of the oldest church in the city.
It must be right. "
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants, in which the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on guard.
And the concerns about Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Floridareiseführer changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often forgotten centre of Florida, to the locations of black history and human drama.
Naughty as Oskar in real life as well as in literature, Hurston led readers to the shop of Eatonville ’ s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Away from the road to the left," she wrote, "there is the brown-white-painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always cares about, although he can hardly read and write."
She also mentioned the new widow Dash's husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and whatever fits with the hour rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were," said Ella Dinkins, 90 years old, one of the Johnson's maidens who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty, full of sexual allusions.
She added: "Some people didn't like this."
You still remember Hurtson as a lively eccentric woman who regularly returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came to the city, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in trousers, in a city that even today imagines something on its venerable clothing style.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, whereas many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora," said Mr Franklin.
But "she never stayed too long," he added while he was rocking in his chair, on a backward terrace facing Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960 she was poor and her books were sold out.
Together with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived, in an anonymous grave.
In Eatonville there was no big commemoration, no large public readings.
"I don't think they have understood their contribution in the world or their heritage in the least," says Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to lay a five-lane highway through the city to replace the Kennedy Boulevard, the slow two-lane main street of the municipality.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed the highway 4 through the western outskirts.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the struggle against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"During this time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff on the off-seated people," said Mr. Franklin.
"There was even once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car. "
In 1955, in a letter to Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's request to force integration by calling its decision against the School Council in the Brown case "insulting rather than respecting my race."
People today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its young people.
"Black children were used to being embraced - I remember - by hugging their teacher in the morning and hugging their teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the non-profit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there is a cultural divide," said Mrs. Nathiri.
However, civil rights have helped to make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons - black authors, actors and artists who overlooked prejudices as they did, with positive self-confidence and statements like: "How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand. "
In 1975, the writer Alice Walker set out for Hurston ’ s nameless grave and began to fight for the revival of her glory.
Five years later, a much-praised Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves and once again made it part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came exactly at a time when Eatonville ’ s most famous daughter once again stood in the light of the public.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a saviour.
The municipality began planning a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road maps.
"The plans of a five-lane highway animated the city, accelerated it with top speed, awakened genuine citizens' pride," said Mrs. Nathiri.
Mrs Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the city ’ s self-image.
There were more and more visitors, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to appreciate the past anew.
Eatonville was incorporated into the national historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (naturally named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a peculiarity in Florida: only 6 miles from Orlando city centre, it can sometimes feel like a backstreet in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90% black nowadays.)
Outsiders in search of the history of Eatonville and its meaning are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews a permit is necessary in advance and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, which was painted by a white man and represents black men in the field work - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, self-confident teacher with a preference for dark red, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that Hurston was becoming bigger, a higher degree of home pride was born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as much as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed like any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin ’ s nephew, the 18 year-old Edwin Harvey, who is planning to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or with the police who, according to him, could use some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most of the people who only pass through here will think," Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others, "said Alondra Kenon on a Sunday after the church.
"But if you actually stop and look at your story for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
