A flamenco dancer from Seville venerates a dancer who also comes from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Katalane (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and her mother Andalusia (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the district of Triana and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and expert for oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first female fighters for the emancipation of the woman, such as Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, vegetarian, and stood up for the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
Isabel Bayón fascinated the life of this woman, who left her mark on the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe in the time between the wars.
'I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this role to me, which seemed impossible to me. '
'We don't try to tell about her life, but to keep her Esprit, 'said the flamenco dancer.
Their dance bases helped me a lot in Flamenco.
For example, 'The Dance of the Butterfly' seemed to me like Guajira, or 'The Dance of the Serpent' like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area, 'she claims.
The production anticipates two extraordinary collaborations: with Miguel Poveda, who will sing for Isabel once again at one of her performances, as he did in 'La puerta abierta'; and with Flamenco champion Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work together with one of her former pupils.
'Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work and I feel very honoured. '
The production also counts on musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the singing of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Júarez, he 'takes on the role of the companion of the artists who were Divas, in whom he constantly falls in love.'
In this work, one also tells in a certain way about the life of this woman, who became known in places as far away as India, the United States or Russia, and also throughout Europe, although she usually lived in London.
'I wanted to recall her, because I think she is one of the women who have an enormous influence on a particular epoch and whose works nowadays nobody knows more and therefore she appreciates even less, 'Bayón claims.
