According to reports from Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema and Quebec, who is responsible for Quebec, and Canadian blood society to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
'In 1998, when Hema and Quebec started their work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood canning system in Quebec, Dr. Décary remembers.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through the work in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence, 'she says, before she proudly stresses that at the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of the population had Quebec's confidence in Hema.
Dr. Décary, however, maintains that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its founding on September 28, 1998, Quebec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the appearance of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new species of Creutzfeldt's disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its foundation in 1998.
'And we did not have the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we referred to one of the main directives of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is evidently the case with the Creutzfeldt and Jakob of the disease, which manifests itself through a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
Thus, in April 1999, blood was not assumed by people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more precise method of detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which allow the detection of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation period, which takes place between the time at which the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not see it, was substantially reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV infected blood.
In other words, this means that 12 million canned blood would have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema and Quebec distributed between 400,000 and 500,000 canned blood each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case where HIV was transmitted via a blood conserve occurs.
I think you can feel comfortable nowadays when you get or prescribe blood transfusion to restore your health, 'says the head of the Hema department of Quebec.
'Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
One never knows which pathogens can enter the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya -virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil -virus, is transmitted through insects through the blood.
We need to continuously monitor ', continues Dr. Décary, before she stresses that, in addition to a safe supply, Hema and Quebec must also provide adequate supply.
'Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
As treatments to combat cancer are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which on average only 3% of the inhabitants of Quebecs suitable for donation. '
Every healthy person who is 18 years or older and fulfils the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted, for example because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from donation for one year.
'With these 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of stocks are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network when they grow older and can no longer donate blood.
It is hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep it and make it become regular donors.
Today life is so hectic that one rarely finds the time to spend an hour donating blood, 'regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema provides Quebec not only with blood preserves, but also with human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which are almost exclusively used for serious fire injuries.
