Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech of Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice Director General of the Canadian gold mine Barrick Gold.
It confirms, and pursues an Orwellian logic, that the world ’ s largest gold extraction company sought a libel lawsuit of over six million against three authors and a small medium-sized publishing house, with the aim of opening a ‘ public transparent debate ’.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of libel actions, but on the law.
As expected, Mr Garver completely concealed this fundamental difference.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to ruin everyone who dares to represent one of their opposing opinions.
No matter how the trial proceeds, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal battles is, moreover, often to ruin the defenders in order to force an amicable regulation, which makes the opposite side mouth-dead and also deterrents anyone who dares to deal again with the question.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things before public opinion.
In contrast to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick works gold, debates are usually conducted in Canada through the exchange of ideas and not through blows.
It would therefore have been enough if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent audit teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have any confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters to support the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can ask for a 'public' debate at the same time, while disregarding the opinions of this very public?
Apparently, this word in the vice-president world only includes the generously paid lawyers, not the community of all Canadians; a very narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public, which supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada, does so mainly because it rejects the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is prepared to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not within a framework that many perceive as a gagging complaint (in the course of the 'public debate' Barrick Gold has just made a request to the authors of Noir Canada, in which she demands that they no longer use this term...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's complaint is a direct attack on the freedom to conduct academic research and the truth that is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss topics that the rich companies of this world do not like, who else can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to handle debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The disproportionate lawsuit by Barrick Gold clearly shows that, unlike what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit this type of unjustified lawsuits.
Rescue for Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans understand each other
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans, and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis, which has been shaking Wall Street for months, still needs to be adopted by the two Congress Chambers.
The main issues are: better control of Members of Parliament over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to secure the repayment of public funds used, new orders to curb the number of houses paved for payment arrears, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the management staff of the supported companies.
The American Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, the President of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative, Senator Judd Gregg, who was present at the negotiations announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news, after a two-day negotiation marathon.
'We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be market-effective ', said the Bush administration representative, Henry Paulson.
'It was all about protecting the real economy and the American people from the curriculum crisis on Wall Street, 'the democrat said.
‘ This is the fundamental point: unless we do, the trauma, chaos and unrest in American daily life will be enormous, ’ said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated during the last two hours, out of fear of the effect that a renewed failure would have had on the mood of investors.
The deadline agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who were late in the negotiations, were more likely to be supporters of the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to hit them in this extreme way.
The Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain orders to the agreement, especially those to allow owners to keep their homes, and those that affect the salaries of senior employees of the state-rescued companies.
'If you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people, that is not what you could congratulate.
