It comes 14 months after a crisis, triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble, which initially led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprime) before expanding to other forms of more widespread bonds (PCAA), and eventually led to a freeze in financial power and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MEPs who failed last week the first attempt to reach agreement.
Since the Democrats accepted that certain 'toxic' assets of societies should only be secured and not bought by the government in distress, the impasse is believed to escape.
To round off the perspective for everyone in Congress, a decree has also been added stating that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it would then be able to levy new taxes to reclaim its capital.
