The Psychology of Surrendering - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the file offering.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play Lotto while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the opponent's overbid plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore said that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have carried out additional investigations into the pursuit of money.
In this case, three groups should offer against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their inserts.
Another group was also promised $15 reward if they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in case of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was only that the emphasis was on one on winning, while the other on losing.
However, as proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "anti-losing" playing group were ready for higher missions than those in the control or "gain" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have so far only justified the behaviour observed at auctions with the pleasure of winning or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready "- said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When is the doctor visiting?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated at one hundred thousand in Germany, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, vaginal secretion or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to vaccinate against viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two or three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die annually from hepatitis B, much more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people are in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen secretly destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20 to 30 years.
Timely prevention, such as regular inspection, is therefore essential.
There are three groups in which this disease occurs more frequently: those who underwent blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C sufferers worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
As the disease is already detectable during routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognised in due time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, organized for the first time by patient representatives worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, its origin and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
The latest research shows that religious faith acts as a kind of "painkiller", which is supposed to have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: The British newspaper Telegraph reported on the extent to which faith in God influences human pain.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
With the help of a brain Scan technology, it was even proven that the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project in which not only scientists but also philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participate.
When the test subjects were tried, a sparkling device was connected to the left hand, which released the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to concentrate heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a painting of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of religious trance among the faithful, while they chose da Vinci ’ s image because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt reassuring.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, and in that time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they were supposed to see either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they had felt "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "cared for", and they had felt "calm and peace".
During the viewing of the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than if they had Leonardo ’ s work before their eyes.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be caused by other strongly acting images, even among atheists, but one would have to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find an image that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
The Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practising the faith should change our personality and do so in many cases," Wright said.
According to these outstanding results, the only question remains is what effect a Madonna ’ s image of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
You are what you communicate about you
