Intelligent car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new technologies for accident prevention if not to imitate the obstacle to sensors from nature?
For example, that of bees.
An amazing project was presented at CEATEC in Japan, where the Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees in the creation of new accident avoidance systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In the flight each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology and PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in every direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to imitate the function of the compound eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the car robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of bees by turning the tires around the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If it were not so, the car robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," explained Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable.
The entire process must reflect the bees ’ behavior when they evade other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to bees, dodging cannot take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, namely only in the direction of the twisting of the tires.
While the bees are open to endless possibilities to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotary motion or the acceleration and braking of the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium and polymer batteries, which are lighter and more energy-efficient, and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium and ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on data processing, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process some inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction by means of previous maneuvers, so that it constantly takes only a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabytes and megabytes of heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which, according to Nissan, will be standard in production within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS ’ s satellite navigation by consciously directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
