Napolitano: "Prevention against accidents at work is crucial"
Every day 2,500 accidents occur in Italy, three people die and 27 remain lifelong invalids.
For 2007, the data of the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were around 1200.
These figures show the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) in all the provinces of Italy will celebrate the 58th national day for victims of accidents at work, in order to draw the attention of social institutions and media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data distributed by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention in the workplace is", confirms the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The Head of State expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention of jobs, to the protection of injured workers, to aid the families of victims and to raise public awareness".
"An outrageous" Basta "has risen up to this; understandable in the case of tragedies that, in terms of their magnitude, trigger some vortices in the media and public participation. However, the everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even be repeated in their own dynamics".
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness of the school framework on the part of young people who nurture the world of work are particularly important.
It is our duty to draw attention to this phenomenon and not to distract it from its social seriousness; we must put in place and improve a legislative norm.
On the one hand, the President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths is an urgent social emergency that offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards firm rules aimed at putting an end to the problem".
"The data on accidents at work seem to signal a slight improvement, but this does not exclude that the number of work-related deaths is far too high", emphasizes President of Anmil Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this" positive tendency "to mean less attention. That's exactly what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How do you believe that you are basically doing too little to counter the phenomenon of accidents? You can fight against it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary - according to Mercandelli, but also stronger measures to educate the workers who are already beginning at school ".
"A further effort is necessary - he adds - in terms of communication and awareness of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers is needed towards a phenomenon that represents a social emergency ".
Mercandelli also referred to "the progressive deterioration of protection for workers' victims" and denounced the "abolition of the social system against which we have been fighting in recent years".
"The aim is therefore to give the worker a guarantee of insurance, so that the fate of the victim of a work accident does not depend on voluntary or accidental donations, which from time to time are decided by a legislator".
Mp3 -Player under indictment: risk of hearing damage
Listening to lute music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 player, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which cited the opinion of the Csrseri (Scientific Committee on Current and Recently Identified Health Risks) of the EU in a report published in Brussels today.
"The report - as stated in a note - makes it clear that 5% of those who listen to loud music with portable music devices for at least five years weekly longer than an hour a day risk the permanent loss of their hearing."
"I am worried that such a large number of young people, who usually put portable music devices and mobile phones at a high volume, will irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings - it is said on the part of the Eu - there is a clear risk that urges rapid action.
What really matters is to raise consumer awareness and make this information common.
In view of these scientific findings, we need to review the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology ".
Brussels had appointed the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music equipment among young people.
"The scientists, concluding the EU Communication, confirm that they are rightly concerned and that the Commission, together with the other members of the Eu and those affected, will now investigate the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music devices and similar devices".
At the moment, there is already a European standard that limits the level of noise from portable music devices to 100 dB, the concern about the damage that could result from too much noise.
One can very restrict this damage by using solutions such as the reduction of volume and the length of noise exposure.
In its report, the Eu's Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable music devices listen to loud (louder than 89 decibels) music only five hours a week, the statutory limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who cross this limit risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
That is 5% to 10% of users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the Eu.
