The elite is in danger
The phenomenon was already revealed a few days ago, when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the White House ’ s $700 billion austerity package: a large part of the Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday ’ s edition of the New York Times, which reports how the crisis is dividing the Republican Party, which is increasingly dividing itself into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which always favored the state institutions and the business community, and those neo-conservatives who are hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world, and who, in particular, win voters in the south and at the heart of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise mainly to the voice of what I mentioned above.
This example is, however, only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake announces or even already represents: not only in the US, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond it will be affected.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-feared events, which finally take shape and come to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis means a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close ties with foreign countries and at the same time manage a vast amount of private households living in a single state.
This means an immediate political problem for governments: how to behave towards the families concerned, which also represent an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis appears economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have been disconnected and lost its right to speak: the EU has given clear proof of this, which, due to its division into different national and international conflicts, does not know how to find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects their own state to intervene; rescue plans, new rules, and, most importantly, distribution of aid funds: since the crisis became ever more serious, only the US has to save itself in the economic situation without foreign aid.
And in addition to the means they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two conditions that cannot be overvalued - under certain circumstances - which otherwise probably no international organisation and no market will be able to resort to in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the national element of the state is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that is recently associated with a closely related sector in the economy: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered into a networked whole empire, into a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we have to realize at once how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to the other of the world, but are nevertheless extremely connected to a strictly circumscribed piece of earth - a territory.
Therefore, the one who possesses such a territory is advantageous to another who lives in an area without harvest, without water or free from oil.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, presupposes a brief insertion.
Who says territory, who government, who says politics, also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaders, especially those of the economy, which turned out to be insufficient and full of shadows.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a sense, still worrying aspect: a loss of confidence, intolerance, an image of inexpediency, a sense of distance, all aimed at a whole class of Western leaders.
In this way, the conviction among large parts of the population seems to pave the way, that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their Way of Life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content represents itself to the majority as increasingly foreign and more traditional.
The demand for leadership thus nourishes underground a branched but powerful movement of disempowerment of the leading class and the conventional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of voters and in the unmediated upswing of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, over the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, towards the rebellion of American deputies against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectuals, creditors, some would say their format, more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value with regard to what is happening today in the lower social strata of the West, and which is being intensified and driven by the financial crisis to the point of over-dimensionality.
In view of all this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping the eyes wide open is certainly not.
