Medicines: never use fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin wealth, can cause serious health damage if they are taken at the same time with certain vital medications, since they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, Professor of the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of packaged as well as fresh fruit juices in conjunction with drug intake. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he once again raised the alarm: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is sufficient to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital medicines to the extent that they are virtually eliminated and thus endanger the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice has already been suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
MEDICAMENTS IN GEFAHR - The same agency of the medicine had warned doctors and patients in a report two years ago against the dangers of this mix, and stressed to pay attention to what is drunk in conjunction with means such as diazepan or metadone.
IT IS NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT - According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Therefore, Michele Carruba, Director of the Università Statale di Milano, said: "Such results are usually immediately passed on to the various international manufacturers who are free to change consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the leaflet and, if there are still ambiguities, to have no fear of having a pharmacist or physician to ask, "emphasizes the expert of the ANSA agency.
