This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening in the large urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means in the long run death for the one-room cinema in the centre. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the traits of a cultural crime.
The film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who 20 years ago brought him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the vast amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these mines paid for most of the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
