When the energy springs from the waves, the big ones suddenly run up
It is a never-ending source of money that covers more than 70% of the planet ’ s surface, and only now does it seem to understand the world ’ s major energy companies.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking for, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of gaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; not accidentally, these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed in 1980, the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now environmental organisations and the rise in oil prices are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world ’ s energy demand could be met by ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power stations.
In addition, there are the currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract to build a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are now focusing on marine energy production.
"Chevron investigates these technologies," according to the spokesman of a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, and weighs the possibility of working with us. "
This is about obtaining an authorisation from the American Energy Commission, which is needed to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil is still being extracted by the US, especially in Alaska, and that President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
Besides Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; the details are not known, as observers talk about an increasing interest.
Technologies that are yet to be improved.
Experts are talking about technology that is still in progress, not least because the last doubts have not yet been clarified by environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are different possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmers via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipes.
Until now, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only waiting for the state approval. Part of the energy gained could also be used for military installations.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a shopping cottage and a park set using undersea turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotation movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorization to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Recovery Research, a particular interest immediately deserves the potential that lies in tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more trustworthy power source.
Tidal energy in particular is what led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to already invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 - up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
